203
00:09:59,853 --> 00:10:02,515
<i>Unfortunately,</i>
<i>Kitty was meeting with Gob at the time.</i>

204
00:10:02,623 --> 00:10:06,354
- What about hash browns?
- No, because hash browns are potatoes.

205
00:10:06,460 --> 00:10:08,860
So you really can't
eat anything on this diet.

206
00:10:08,962 --> 00:10:12,056
Wow. Wonder how this
is gonna affect my honey business?

207
00:10:12,166 --> 00:10:14,566
Gob, I have seen you
get passed over...

208
00:10:14,668 --> 00:10:16,966
time and time again
by your family.

209
00:10:17,070 --> 00:10:19,334
You don't deserve that.
You're smarter than them.

210
00:10:19,439 --> 00:10:24,172
What about macaroni...
let me finish... salad?

211
00:10:24,278 --> 00:10:26,769
Gob, this is your time.

212
00:10:26,880 --> 00:10:29,781
With my help,
knowing what I know...

213
00:10:29,883 --> 00:10:34,013
- we could take over the Bluth Company together.
- Wow!

214
00:10:34,121 --> 00:10:36,555
This is a side of you
I'd never noticed before.

215
00:10:36,657 --> 00:10:40,184
Have they always
been that big?

216
00:10:40,294 --> 00:10:42,387
<i>[Narrator] And the next day,</i>
<i>Michael went to his mother's.</i>

217
00:10:42,496 --> 00:10:45,522
I saw an exposé
on the Iraq palaces last night...

218
00:10:45,632 --> 00:10:48,192
and I could have sworn that one of them
was the Sea Wind unit.

219
00:10:48,302 --> 00:10:52,864
That's funny. I always pictured Iraq
in the middle of the desert.

220
00:10:52,973 --> 00:10:54,634
Dad sold houses to the Iraqis,
didn't he?

221
00:10:54,741 --> 00:10:57,266
And this is what you kept from me
so I could take the polygraph test.

222
00:10:57,377 --> 00:11:00,540
Tell me the truth, okay? 'Cause there's been
a lot of lying in this family.

223
00:11:00,647 --> 00:11:02,638
And a lot of love.

224
00:11:02,749 --> 00:11:05,274
- More lies.
- Look, I never knew about anything.

225
00:11:05,385 --> 00:11:07,683
But I had my suspicions.

226
00:11:07,788 --> 00:11:09,688
He never told me
where he was going...

227
00:11:09,790 --> 00:11:13,385
but he used to come back from those
business trips reeking of lamb.

228
00:11:13,493 --> 00:11:16,360
<i>And people would send figs</i>...
<i>not even at Christmas.</i>

229
00:11:16,463 --> 00:11:18,829
In the middle of October.

230
00:11:18,932 --> 00:11:21,162
Oh, and once,
someone sent him a toe...

231
00:11:21,268 --> 00:11:23,361
and he went white
as a sheet.

232
00:11:23,470 --> 00:11:26,564
- I think you're right, Michael.
- <i>[Door Opens]</i>

233
00:11:26,673 --> 00:11:30,074
<i>Zero hour, Michael.</i>
<i>It's the end of the line.</i>

234
00:11:30,177 --> 00:11:33,806
I'm the first born.
Sick of playing second fiddle.

235
00:11:33,914 --> 00:11:37,179
Always third in line for everything.
Tired of finishing fourth.

236
00:11:37,284 --> 00:11:39,752
Being the fifth wheel.

237
00:11:39,853 --> 00:11:42,287
There are six things
I'm mad about...

238
00:11:42,389 --> 00:11:45,256
- and I'm taking over.
- You want to be in charge?

239
00:11:45,359 --> 00:11:47,520
- Yeah.
- You want to deal with what I deal with...

240
00:11:47,628 --> 00:11:50,995
a sister who takes your money
and throws it away;

241
00:11:51,098 --> 00:11:52,998
a mother
who you can't trust;

242
00:11:53,100 --> 00:11:56,228
a company whose founder
may be on trial for treason...

243
00:11:56,336 --> 00:11:58,600
Is that what you want?

244
00:11:58,705 --> 00:12:03,142
- What kind of vacation time does it offer?
- Yeah.

245
00:12:03,243 --> 00:12:07,612
<i>[Narrator] Gob realized that the power play</i>
<i>he promised to make with Kitty...</i>

246
00:12:07,714 --> 00:12:10,774
- <i>had perhaps come at a bad time.</i>
- I've made a huge mistake.

247
00:12:10,884 --> 00:12:12,319
<i>And Tobias was having</i>
<i>his first book reading.</i>

248
00:12:12,319 --> 00:12:13,217
<i>And Tobias was having</i>
<i>his first book reading.</i>

249
00:12:13,320 --> 00:12:16,847
And, for the ease of the reader, I have
changed all the gender-related pronouns...

250
00:12:16,957 --> 00:12:19,858
"he," "she"...
to the masculine "he."

251
00:12:19,960 --> 00:12:24,260
<i>"The Man Inside Me.</i>
For Lindsay, my rock.

252
00:12:24,364 --> 00:12:26,855
I could not have done this
without him."

253
00:12:28,402 --> 00:12:31,132
<i>[Narrator] And Lindsay arrived</i>
<i>to support her husband.</i>

254
00:12:31,238 --> 00:12:35,698
"For there is a man inside me,
and only when he's finally out...

255
00:12:35,809 --> 00:12:39,210
can I walk free of pain."

256
00:12:39,313 --> 00:12:41,747
This book is gonna sell,
like, a billion copies.

257
00:12:41,848 --> 00:12:44,976
<i>Lindsay!</i>
<i>Oh, I'm so glad you came.</i>

258
00:12:45,085 --> 00:12:47,019
I was hoping for more women.

259
00:12:47,120 --> 00:12:49,486
Perhaps I shouldn't have just used "he."
I think that was a mistake.

260
00:12:49,589 --> 00:12:53,753
<i>And Lindsay realized that Tobias was just</i>
<i>as oblivious as she'd always thought.</i>

261
00:12:53,860 --> 00:12:56,385
Tobias, I don't think
this relationship is gonna work.

262
00:12:56,496 --> 00:12:59,522
What are you talking about?
We've had some great times.

263
00:13:01,735 --> 00:13:04,670
We've got nothing left,
Tobias.

264
00:13:04,771 --> 00:13:07,137
<i>And Michael went</i>
<i>to confront his father.</i>

265
00:13:07,240 --> 00:13:10,835
You're building houses in Iraq? I mean,
do you know how they punish treason?

266
00:13:10,944 --> 00:13:13,174
- First time.
- I've never heard of a second.

267
00:13:13,280 --> 00:13:15,874
Oh, I've got the worst...
[Beeps] attorneys.

268
00:13:15,982 --> 00:13:19,008
This is why I didn't want to get you
involved, but we can fix this.

269
00:13:19,119 --> 00:13:21,212
- What are Kitty's demands? What does she want?
- She wants my job.

270
00:13:21,321 --> 00:13:23,289
Suddenly everybody wants my job,
and I should've given it to her.

271
00:13:23,390 --> 00:13:27,690
You mean, you didn't? Michael! She has
the evidence of what we did over there.

272
00:13:27,794 --> 00:13:30,285
No, all she thinks it is
is unpaid taxes.

273
00:13:30,397 --> 00:13:33,230
Yeah. What if she gives it to someone
who's even moderately intelligent?

274
00:13:33,333 --> 00:13:36,393
<i>[Narrator] In fact, Kitty had gone</i>
<i>to someone moderately intelligent...</i>

275
00:13:36,503 --> 00:13:39,563
<i>in her continuing quest for</i>
<i>control of the Bluth Company.</i>

276
00:13:39,673 --> 00:13:43,404
- I can't believe you called me for a date.
- You didn't tell anyone, did you?

277
00:13:43,510 --> 00:13:46,445
Are you kidding?
I don't need to brag...

278
00:13:46,546 --> 00:13:49,140
<i>that some people haven't</i>
<i>even been on a date!</i>

279
00:13:49,249 --> 00:13:51,649
Day not over yet, fatty.

280
00:13:51,752 --> 00:13:54,118
<i>You weren't thinking clearly.</i>
<i>I mean, none of us are.</i>

281
00:13:54,221 --> 00:13:56,121
We need bread.

282
00:13:56,223 --> 00:13:58,714
If this information was so damaging,
why didn't you just shred it?

283
00:13:58,825 --> 00:14:01,225
Well, Saddam
owed us money.

284
00:14:01,328 --> 00:14:04,126
You didn't realize
that he wouldn't pay?

285
00:14:04,231 --> 00:14:06,256
Your mom had a good
feeling about him.

286
00:14:06,366 --> 00:14:11,770
<i>So Mom knew this entire time, and shejust</i>
<i>lied to my face for months and months?</i>

287
00:14:11,872 --> 00:14:15,603
Let me tell you something, Dad. This is...
This is your problem. Okay? Not mine.

288
00:14:15,709 --> 00:14:19,805
Well, maybe it wouldn't be my problem
if you did what I asked for once in your life...

289
00:14:19,913 --> 00:14:23,041
- and you gave Kitty what I asked you to!
- Once in my damn life?

290
00:14:23,150 --> 00:14:26,142
All I've ever done my entire life is do
exactly what you told me to, all right?

291
00:14:26,253 --> 00:14:30,246
I've done everything for this family, Pop.
Not anymore. Kitty can have my job.

292
00:14:30,357 --> 00:14:32,917
And you can take your own
polygraph test, 'cause I'm done.

293
00:14:33,026 --> 00:14:36,120
- I'm done with you,
and I'm done with the business.
- <i>Great.</i>

294
00:14:36,229 --> 00:14:40,529
I'm gonna get a lethal injection
because my son won't eat a potato.

295
00:14:44,304 --> 00:14:46,966
<i>[Narrator]</i>
<i>George Sr., in a surprise move...</i>

296
00:14:47,073 --> 00:14:49,234
<i>volunteered to take</i>
<i>the polygraph.</i>

297
00:14:49,342 --> 00:14:51,367
- So did you swipe the sedative
from the infirmary...
- No!

298
00:14:51,478 --> 00:14:53,708
- to lower your heart rate?
- No! It's okay. I want to do this...

299
00:14:53,814 --> 00:14:57,147
because I want people to know
I never willfully deceived anyone.

300
00:14:57,250 --> 00:15:00,344
Mistakes were made,
but I never intended to hurt anyone!

301
00:15:00,454 --> 00:15:02,012
<i>I was trying to support</i>
<i>my family!</i>

302
00:15:02,122 --> 00:15:04,352
- He doesn't appear to be on a sedative.
- But I can see clearly now...

303
00:15:04,458 --> 00:15:09,054
sitting in this chair, strapped to this machine,
I can see that my life has become a failure!

304
00:15:09,162 --> 00:15:12,495
<i>I've let people down,</i>
<i>let myself down.</i>

305
00:15:12,599 --> 00:15:16,228
But I love my country!
I love it here!

306
00:15:16,336 --> 00:15:18,998
You can shop... I love my...
Can't breathe.

307
00:15:19,105 --> 00:15:22,836
- I can't breathe!
- Wait! Wait! Are you guilty? Yes or no?

308
00:15:22,943 --> 00:15:25,605
- I think he's having a heart attack.
- <i>That was not a nod. No.</i>

309
00:15:25,712 --> 00:15:28,704
- That was not a nod.
- Call an ambulance!

310
00:15:28,815 --> 00:15:30,908
[Siren Wailing]

311
00:15:32,285 --> 00:15:35,550
- Oh, how is he?
- Stable.

312
00:15:35,655 --> 00:15:38,852
But they don't know
if he's due for another one.

313
00:15:38,959 --> 00:15:43,089
It's his own fault. What kind of diet is this?
It's too much meat.

314
00:15:43,196 --> 00:15:46,290
I want all of you
off this immediately.

315
00:15:46,399 --> 00:15:49,129
Except you.

316
00:15:49,236 --> 00:15:51,898
<i>Tobias!</i>
<i>I can't believe you came!</i>

317
00:15:52,005 --> 00:15:55,031
Oh, come on, Lindsay.
This is my family.

318
00:15:55,141 --> 00:15:58,872
<i>[Narrator] And Lindsay realized that</i>
<i>perhaps they did have something left</i>...

319
00:15:58,979 --> 00:16:00,537
<i>a real connection.</i>

320
00:16:00,647 --> 00:16:03,207
Also, Dale, one of the gentlemen
from my reading...

321
00:16:03,316 --> 00:16:06,149
is a nurse here, so we were able
to park right out front.

322
00:16:08,021 --> 00:16:09,921
Oh! Barry.
Did you talk to a doctor?

323
00:16:10,023 --> 00:16:12,719
I did.
I have poison oak.

324
00:16:12,826 --> 00:16:15,556
Do you believe it?
Where the hell did I get that?

325
00:16:15,662 --> 00:16:17,562
<i>[Dog Barks]</i>

326
00:16:17,664 --> 00:16:20,394
- She was talking about George.
- No, he's the same.

327
00:16:20,500 --> 00:16:24,402
Look, I guess we should decide who's
gonna speak for the family. I would...

328
00:16:24,504 --> 00:16:26,062
but I have Laker tickets.

329
00:16:26,172 --> 00:16:28,072
<i>[Dog Barks]</i>

330
00:16:28,174 --> 00:16:30,074
<i>[Narrator]</i>
<i>Buster knew this was his chance...</i>

331
00:16:30,176 --> 00:16:32,110
<i>to put Kitty's coup d'état</i>
<i>in action.</i>

332
00:16:32,212 --> 00:16:34,510
<i>He wondered</i>
<i>ifhe was up for it.</i>

333
00:16:34,614 --> 00:16:37,082
Someone might have to sign
the "do not resuscitate" form.

334
00:16:37,183 --> 00:16:41,244
- <i>And he decided he wasn't.</i>
- I need to make a telephone call.
Get out of something.

335
00:16:41,354 --> 00:16:43,447
I'm in charge now.

336
00:16:43,557 --> 00:16:45,752
I speak for this family.

337
00:16:45,859 --> 00:16:49,454
<i>I mean, l-I could,</i>
<i>if you wanted me to.</i>

338
00:16:49,563 --> 00:16:53,260
I'd rather not, obviously.
Don't know what I'd say.

339
00:16:53,366 --> 00:16:55,926
Why do I have to be the one?
I don't need this.

340
00:16:56,036 --> 00:16:58,300
<i>Why does this have to</i>
<i>become my problem? No. I'm out.</i>

341
00:16:58,405 --> 00:17:00,532
Forget it. Find somebody else.
I'm sick of it.

342
00:17:00,640 --> 00:17:04,269
- I'm sick of doing everything for this family.
- Where is Michael?

343
00:17:04,377 --> 00:17:06,607
- [Scoffs] Typical.
- Did somebody call him?

344
00:17:06,713 --> 00:17:08,704
<i>[Narrator]</i>
<i>In fact, they hadn't.</i>

345
00:17:08,815 --> 00:17:11,443
<i>And at that moment,</i>
<i>he was determined to finally get...</i>

346
00:17:11,551 --> 00:17:13,781
- <i>as far away from his family as possible.</i>
- Hey, pal.

347
00:17:13,887 --> 00:17:16,117
- Pack your bags.
- Where are we goin'?

348
00:17:16,222 --> 00:17:19,316
Anywhere. Joshua Tree, space camp,
the Baseball Hall of Fame...

349
00:17:19,426 --> 00:17:22,953
Everything you and I have always wanted to do
but haven't been able to because of this family.

350
00:17:23,063 --> 00:17:25,793
- We're just gonna go?
- Yeah. And I don't know
if we're even gonna come back.

351
00:17:25,899 --> 00:17:28,459
- There's nothing keeping us here.
- Well, Dad...

352
00:17:28,568 --> 00:17:32,004
- I like it here.
- What the hell's going on with you lately?

353
00:17:32,105 --> 00:17:35,268
I wanted to watch <i>Hindsight,</i>
and you weren't there.

354
00:17:35,375 --> 00:17:38,310
I want to pack up and desert the family,
and you don't want to.

355
00:17:38,411 --> 00:17:41,346
- Is it this new girlfriend?
- No, it...

356
00:17:41,448 --> 00:17:45,077
It's because of the family.
I like the family.

357
00:17:45,185 --> 00:17:48,916
- I mean, if we leave, who's
gonna take care of these people?
- I don't know.

358
00:17:49,022 --> 00:17:53,322
The state or the police. Maybe the
Magicians' Alliance will pick up some slack.

359
00:17:53,426 --> 00:17:56,361
- <i>[Phone Ringing]</i>
- Hey. That's gonna be them, and
they're gonna want something.

360
00:17:56,463 --> 00:17:58,590
We're not answering that.

361
00:17:58,698 --> 00:18:01,667
<i>[Ringing Continues]</i>

362
00:18:05,639 --> 00:18:07,539
Hello?

363
00:18:08,775 --> 00:18:11,767
- Where's George Michael?
- Exactly. Where is he?

364
00:18:11,878 --> 00:18:15,177
Ever since he's been dating this
Annie McNo-face, he's been blowing me off.

365
00:18:15,281 --> 00:18:17,511
- Oh, hey. Where's Pop-Pop?
- Room 212.

366
00:18:17,617 --> 00:18:19,185
<i>[Narrator]</i>
<i>And that's when Maeby decided...</i>

367
00:18:19,185 --> 00:18:20,083
<i>[Narrator]</i>
<i>And that's when Maeby decided...</i>

368
00:18:20,186 --> 00:18:24,247
<i>that perhaps she could use her uncle</i>
<i>to make her cousin jealous.</i>

369
00:18:27,260 --> 00:18:29,524
Hey, Dad.
Wait up.

370
00:18:29,629 --> 00:18:32,291
That was a waste
of time.

371
00:18:34,234 --> 00:18:36,930
- [Groaning]
- How's he doin'?

372
00:18:37,037 --> 00:18:39,198
He's hanging in there.

373
00:18:39,305 --> 00:18:41,705
<i>He keeps trying to get this I. V.</i>
<i>out ofhis arm. I don't understand why.</i>

374
00:18:41,808 --> 00:18:43,708
<i>It's just glucose.</i>

375
00:18:43,810 --> 00:18:46,210
We're all trying
to stay away from sugar.

376
00:18:48,048 --> 00:18:51,745
- He's gonna be okay, right?
- Absolutely. Absolutely. You all right?

377
00:18:51,851 --> 00:18:54,183
I'll handle
this one, Michael.

378
00:18:54,287 --> 00:18:59,088
Don't you worry. It'll take a lot more
than a heart attack to kill that old bear.

379
00:18:59,192 --> 00:19:01,092
[Laughing]
Old bear!

380
00:19:01,194 --> 00:19:03,094
He likes the honey!

381
00:19:05,365 --> 00:19:07,731
He never got a chance
to see my bee business take off.

382
00:19:07,834 --> 00:19:11,361
Hey, come on, now. Dad's gonna be
around another 30 years, Gob.

383
00:19:11,471 --> 00:19:13,962
Your business,
uh, might not.

384
00:19:15,508 --> 00:19:17,772
You're a good brother,
Michael.

385
00:19:17,877 --> 00:19:21,836
Heart attack never stop
old Big Bear.

386
00:19:21,948 --> 00:19:24,940
I didn't even know
we were calling him Big Bear.

387
00:19:25,051 --> 00:19:28,919
- We never had a chance to!
- Hey, hey. Come on, Gob.

388
00:19:29,022 --> 00:19:33,459
Everybody, I'm very sorry, okay?
I feel awful. I should have been here.

389
00:19:33,560 --> 00:19:36,825
I was the one that was supposed to take that
polygraph test, and then I just turned on him...

390
00:19:36,930 --> 00:19:38,921
<i>and then this happened,</i>
<i>but never again, okay?</i>

391
00:19:39,032 --> 00:19:42,433
I will never, ever leave this family,
no matter what.

392
00:19:43,903 --> 00:19:47,600
- You should've been here.
- I feel like I covered that.

393
00:19:47,707 --> 00:19:50,642
- Well, you didn't say it.
- I feel awful. I should have been here.

394
00:19:50,744 --> 00:19:53,372
Maybe you're right. Maybe I didn't
say it. I should have been here.

395
00:19:55,615 --> 00:19:58,880
- Excuse me, Mr. Bluth.
- Hmm?

396
00:20:00,220 --> 00:20:02,780
- We lost him.
- [All Gasping]

397
00:20:02,889 --> 00:20:06,347
He just, uh, got away from us.
I'm sorry.

398
00:20:07,627 --> 00:20:09,822
<i>Uh, can we go in there?</i>

399
00:20:09,929 --> 00:20:12,397
If you want.
Not a lot to see.

400
00:20:12,499 --> 00:20:15,491
Maybe not for you,
but for us.

401
00:20:30,283 --> 00:20:34,913
<i>[Narrator] And that's when the family</i>
<i>realized that George Sr. wasn't dead...</i>

402
00:20:35,021 --> 00:20:38,081
<i>but was fleeing the country</i>
<i>that he loved so very much.</i>

403
00:20:44,931 --> 00:20:47,866
Pack your bags.

404
00:20:47,967 --> 00:20:50,731
<i>On the next season</i>
<i>of</i> Arrested Development.

405
00:20:50,837 --> 00:20:53,465
<i>The family grapples with the news</i>
<i>they hadjust heard.</i>

406
00:20:53,573 --> 00:20:56,041
Why would a doctor say he's "gone"
when he means he's escaped?

407
00:20:56,142 --> 00:20:58,167
God, I've missed bread.
Mmm.

408
00:20:58,278 --> 00:21:01,441
<i>Wouldn't you say,</i>
<i>"He left out the window'...</i>

409
00:21:01,548 --> 00:21:03,516
or, "The room's empty."

